  "text": "The Fetch API in Firefox consists of four main DOM interfaces. Here is the WebIDL-to-C++ mapping:\n\n1. **Request**: WebIDL at `dom/webidl/Request.webidl` (defines `interface Request`), implemented by `dom/fetch/Request.h` / `dom/fetch/Request.cpp`, with internal representation in `dom/fetch/InternalRequest.h` / `.cpp`.\n\n2. **Response**: WebIDL at `dom/webidl/Response.webidl` (defines `interface Response`), implemented by `dom/fetch/Response.h` / `dom/fetch/Response.cpp`, with internal representation in `dom/fetch/InternalResponse.h` / `.cpp`.\n\n3. **Headers**: WebIDL at `dom/webidl/Headers.webidl` (defines `interface Headers`), implemented by `dom/fetch/Headers.h` / `dom/fetch/Headers.cpp`, with internal representation in `dom/fetch/InternalHeaders.h` / `.cpp`.\n\n4. **FetchEvent**: WebIDL at `dom/webidl/FetchEvent.webidl` (defines `interface FetchEvent : ExtendableEvent`), implemented by the `FetchEvent` class in `dom/serviceworkers/ServiceWorkerEvents.h` / `dom/serviceworkers/ServiceWorkerEvents.cpp`. Note that FetchEvent lives under serviceworkers, not dom/fetch, because it is a ServiceWorker-specific event.\n\nAdditionally, `dom/webidl/Fetch.webidl` defines the `Body` mixin and helper dictionaries, with global fetch() function support in `dom/fetch/Fetch.h` / `dom/fetch/Fetch.cpp`.",
